^b@2zaXXon: Welcome everybody.
 
During the last few weeks we discussed "how to think", how certain thoughts help us to take the right decision more often.
Our investigations were based on bids, made or not, by our opponents. 
In both cases we receive some information that we can use. 
For example:
"He opened 1@h, hence he must have at least 5 hearts and 11 points" or
"He opened 1@c and now I see he is balanced - he has 12-14 points, else he would open 1NT" or
"He passed and later made a 2@c overcall, this should mean he has 5+ (may be 6) clubs and 9-11 points"

Of course, it could be the contrary:
"He has 5 good spades but he did not overcall - probably he doesn't have enough points to overcall" or 
"He has points but he did not overcall - he doesn't have a good suit"
...and so on...

We should track questions like these all the time.
Once you get the picture how one or two suits are divided, 
you should try to imagine the opponent's hands and try to see which hand fits his bids best.
Let us start with our first example!


